<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<pretext xmlns:ns0="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <ns0:include href="../docinfo.ptx" />
  <article>
    
    <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25in" xml:id="ws-volshell">
      <title>Worksheet for Section 7.3</title>

      <objectives>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Compute the volume of a solid of revolution using the shell method.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </objectives>


      <page>
        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p> Let <m>R</m> be the region bounded by <m>y=x^2</m> and the <m>x</m> axis, <m>0 \leq
                x \leq 1</m>. Let <m>S</m> be the solid formed by revolving this region about the <m>
              y</m>-axis. Find the volume of <m>S</m> with the shell method. Sketch <m>R</m>, <m>S</m>,
              and a typical shell. </p>
          </statement>

          </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p> Let <m>R</m> be the region bounded by <m>y=x</m> and <m>y=x^2-2</m>. Let <m>S</m> be
              the solid formed by revolving this region about the line <m>x=3</m>. Find the volume
              of <m>S</m> using the shell method and the washer method. </p>
          </statement>

          </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p> Let <m>R</m> be the region to the right of <m>x=y^2</m>, and to the left of <m>y=2-x</m>
              and <m>y=x-2</m>. Find the volume (choosing your method wisely) of the solid formed by
              revolving <m>R</m> around (a) the <m>x</m>-axis and (b) the <m>y</m>-axis. </p>
          </statement>

          </exercise>
      </page>
      <page>
        <exercisegroup>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              Each integral represents the volume of a solid of revolution. Sketch the region and
              axis of revolution that produce the solid.
            </p>
          </introduction>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\int_{0}^1 2\pi x (x-x^2)\,dx</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <p>
              <m>\int_{0}^2 2\pi (4-y)(2y)\,dy</m>
            </p>
          </exercise>
          <answer>
            <p> The region bounded by <m>y=x</m>, <m>y=-x</m>, <m>y=0</m> and <m>y=2</m>, revolved
              around the line <m>y=4</m>. </p>
          </answer>

        </exercisegroup>
      </page>

      <page>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p> A jewelry bead is formed by drilling a 0.5 cm radius hole from a the center of a
              sphere with radius 1 cm. Explain why the volume of the bead is given by the the
              integral <me>\int_{1/2}^1 4 \pi x \sqrt{1-x^2}\,dx</me> Find the volume. </p>
          </statement>
          </exercise>

        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find the radius of hole in a bead that will make the volume remaining half of the
              original volume.
            </p>
          </statement>
          </exercise>
      </page>
    </worksheet>
